I don't really know what other people are talking about here.  The food is really mediocre at its very best and honestly awful for the most part.  It seems that whoever is cooking learned how to do so at an establishment where excess, low quality grease and monotonous textural elements are the order of the day. For instance, if you like soggy, overcooked calamari, rather than the advertised "crispy" variety, this is your place.  If you enjoy a Bolognese sauce that may have been made a week ago and unceremoniously slopped on some poorly cooked pasta, you ought also to come here.  Finally I don't really know what the menu is trying to achieve, other than taking one dish from each continent and executing it in a way that might make TGI Friday's proud.  You want some Baja fish tacos alongside your poutine and curry bowl? Come on down!  Unfocused and confusing as a whole for a place that looks and sounds like an Irish pub. The beer and such is fine, but nothing they have is really special, you can get it at any bar in the greater Boston area, and pulling pints well isn't exactly difficult, even though two of mine ended up with a third sloshed onto the bar.  Honestly, with plenty of better options around, walk three minutes in either direction and spend your time and money elsewhere.

Lack of service for a person with a disability. Asked to leave! A disgrace! I have never been so poorly treated by  a public establishment in my life. I have disabilities and use a cane, so it is obvious that I need a seat. I realize that the place is crowded. I was there as a guest of a band. After 10 minutes of trying to flag down a person to ask for a table or bar stool, I had to tap a person.                                                                                               I was told by 2 people to leave and come back because they wouldn't be on until later and try and get one then. I mentioned the ADA and reasonable accommodation, and could a gentleman at the bar please give up a seat. When I said that I am a paying customer like everyone else, so could someone please give up a seat. I got smirked at. The post had said 9 on FB.  The first person said, "Well what kind of friends do you have if they didn't tell you they aren't going on until later?" So I went outside in the freezing, windy cold and sat in the window. I asked a friend of the band to please text me when she got there to see if maybe she would get me a seat, hoping that she and the band members would realize that I have a cane and would need a seat. I told her I was sitting outside on the window sill and would be wandering Mass Ave to look for a place to eat. After almost an hour, my knees were swollen and bruised. I went back. I had to explain the same story to the bouncer. I told him I would gladly buy a meal, etc. But the ADA requires reasonable accommodation. The bouncer told me I should go to another establishment to eat. I told him I had tried, but everything was closed. And I was there to see a particular band - one of three - that was supposed to play.  I was insulted. Then I saw my friend and someone else got seated first while I was not seated, standing on one leg and leaning against a wall, in obvious pain. I apologize for getting angry, but I thought the courteous thing to do would have been to offer me a seat, seeing that by that time I was in obvious distress. "Well, there's no seats!," one of them said. At that point, I took an Uber home. Patrons were laughing. I felt disgraced. I have taken the issue up by other means. But I suffered an injury and now have to go to physical therapy.I think customer service - to everyone - should be a priority - to ALL customers. And I shouldn't be looked down upon because I use a cane. Any other place I have gone to had made sure I am seated. Usually the band and/or the staff see to that and thank me for coming.                                                                                                                      I am a professional writer. I also write music reviews for a magazine. What if it had been that night?

Update - I've been getting lunch at the Plough for months. My go-to is the Cuban sandwich, but the last 2 times I've ordered it there was barely anything on the sandwich. Instead of it being loaded with multiple pieces of ham and a health serving of roasted pork, it now has once small slice of ham and a pinch of pork. Normally I would be full after eating this sandwich, but now I'm still hungry after finishing it. I understand if the Plough is trying to pinch some pennies, but don't remove 75% of the contents of sandwiches to do so.  Picked up a Cuban sandwich for lunch, and was pleasantly surprised. It was one of the most delicious sandwiches I have had in a long time. Thank you Plough!

A small, cozy local Irish pub with enough history and character that it's worth crossing town to have a drink there. Plough & Stars has been there I think for more than forty years and, while it's changed owners at least once, it's only gotten better in recent years. It's also the birthplace of Ireland's Connemara whiskey distillery (Ireland's only independent distillery--there's a plaque on the wall about it) and they feature a selection of Connemara whiskeys.  They have an excellent brunch on Sundays, music (mostly rock-n-roll, bluegrass, and blues) most evenings and some afternoons, and in between they always pour a perfect pint. They also have an eclectic selection of beers besides Guinness.  At peak times the service may sometimes be slow or confused, but they're always friendly and inviting.
